                    <history>
                        <origin notBefore="1275" notAfter="1300" cert="high" evidence="conjecture">
                            <p>Written in <origPlace>Iceland</origPlace> assumingly by a Norwegian
                                or a scribe educated in a Norwegian scriptorium due to to the style
                                of writing and language forms exclusively or principally used in
                                Norwegian texts. Kristian Kålund dated it the first half of the
                                thirteenth century, whereas Ole Widding (<bibl>
                                    <ref type="secondary-1" target="Widding655">Widding 1952</ref>
                                    <biblScope unit="pages">163, 171</biblScope>
                                </bibl>) later dated it more correctly to the fourth quarter of the
                                thirteenth century, a dating that later has been agreed by Stéfan
                                Karlsson (<bibl>
                                    <ref type="secondary-1" target="StefKarl44">Stéfan Karlsson
                                        1978</ref>
                                    <biblScope unit="pages">94-95</biblScope>
                                </bibl>).</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The fragment was part of a codex called Höskuldstaðabók, once
                                belonging to the church of Hskuldstair in Húnavatnssýsla. According
                                to the account on the AM-slips it later to <name type="person" key="EinBra001">Einar Brandsson</name> of <name type="place">Galtarnes</name> who also torn it apart belonged was later torn
                                apart by Einar Árni Magnússon possibly owned another two leaves from
                                this mansuscript, containing fragments of Maríu saga and Pétrs saga,
                                however these have gone.</p>
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
